PART B

In this part, we are asked to perform 10-fold cross-validation in training data in order to find the k parameter that will be used in nearest-neighbour (NN) classifier to find the labels of the test instances. As the first step, the three datasets corresponding to x, y and z directions are combined such that each instance has the accelaration information along these directions in order in a row.

As the distance measure, Euclidean and Manhattan distance will be calculated. The k levels that will be tried are 1, 3, 5 and 7. The indices for each fold are generated at the beginning; so that, the same folds can be used in different trials of k and distance measure.

Since distances are calculated, the data should be scaled. With the following code, standardization is done to the data without the class column.

Euclidean Case

For the euclidean distance case, knn() function is used. Its default distance measure is Euclidean distance. For each k value, the same folds are used and the accuracy results for each k value are stored in cvresult table.

##    Method Klev      Accu
## 1:    knn    1 0.9419643
## 2:    knn    3 0.9441964
## 3:    knn    5 0.9408482
## 4:    knn    7 0.9363839

It can be seen that the highest accuracy is achieved when the k value is 3. It minimizes the error, so 3 is chosen as the optimal value.

Manhattan Case

For the Manhattan case, the same procedure is applied. However, kknn() function is used for k-NN classifier. The kknn() function uses Minkowski distance as the distance measure. The p parameter in Minkowski distance is changed in the distance parameter in the kknn() function. When p is 1, it refers to Manhattan distance; so, the distance parameter is set to 1. Additionally, this function uses kernel functions to weight the neighbors according to their distances. In order to use no weights in other words in order to apply standard unweighted knn, kernel parameter is set to rectangular. In the end, the results for different k values are stored in cvresult_manhattan table.

##    Method Klev      Accu
## 1:    knn    1 0.9542411
## 2:    knn    3 0.9553571
## 3:    knn    5 0.9497768
## 4:    knn    7 0.9486607

It can be seen from the table above that the highest accuracy is achieved when the k value is 3. It minimizes the error, so 3 is chosen as the optimal value.

In conclusion, from the training set results, k is chosen to be 3 for both Euclidean and Manhattan distance case.

TASK 2

In this task, we are asked to use ECG time series data used in the class in order to perform logistic regression with fused penalties. Fused lasso penalties tend to make the coefficients of the close variables close to each other. Thus, it penalizes the difference between the coefficients of the observations at time t and t+1. In order to perform logistic regression with fused penalties penalized package is utilized. In penalized package, there are different alternative functions to apply logistic regression with cross-validation. In order to get the optimal lambda value as the output, optL1() function is used for this task.

traindata <- as.data.table(read.table('/Users/elifkonyar/Desktop/IE 582/Codes/NN_Classification/ecgTRAIN'))  
testdata <- as.data.table(read.table('/Users/elifkonyar/Desktop/IE 582/Codes/NN_Classification/ecgTEST'))

PART A

In this part, we are asked to train a logistic regression model on the training data using fused lasso penalties. In the code below, the class information is stored in a seperate table where -1s are updated to 0 for the model building part.

As the next step, logistic regression model is built where fusedl parameter refers to whether it contains the fused penalties or not. Thus, it is set to TRUE. Here, 10-fold cross-validation is applied in the training data in order to obtain the coefficients and the lambda1 value for the model. Lambda2 in this model is 0 by default since we do not apply ridge regression. Epsilon parameter determines the convergence of the objective function. The standardization is done by setting the standardize parameter to TRUE in order to treat all features we have equally. Trace parameter is set to TRUE in order to see the updates in the lambda1 values.

The consecutive nonzero coefficients can be considered to be close mostly as it can be seen inside the purple circles which is by the nature of the fused lasso. Here, the coefficients refer to if the change between the observation number and the next one play a significant role in explaining the class result. For example, if the first coefficient is nonzero (yes, in this case), it means that the change in the second observation compared to the first observation plays a significant role in the class labels.
